D i a g n o s i s: The species is readily distinguished from other West Palaearctic Homalotini by the following character combination: body small (body length: 
1.7-2.5 mm
; length of forebody: 
0.9-1.2 mm
); head approximately as long as broad, widest anteriorly (across eyes); antennae conspicuously incrassate apically, clavate (antennomeres IV-X strongly transverse, at least twice as wide as long); forebody with pronounced microreticulation; punctation of forebody extremely fine, barely noticeable in the microsculpture; elytra much broader than pronotum and posteriorly widened; abdomen broad, widest at segments V or VI, almost as broad as elytra; punctation of abdomen conspicuously sparse and fine, barely noticeable in the microreticulation; median lobe of aedeagus small and with deeply bifid ventral process (
Figs 13-15
); spermatheca (
Fig. 8
) with long and fully developed proximal portion, resembling that of many Athetini. The four-jointed mesotarsus is illustrated in 
Fig. 16.
